Solution Overview
Brief overview
This solution transforms legacy IBM MQ topologies from a raw CSV-based AS-IS state into a simplified, standardized, and automation-ready TARGET architecture. It does this by combining topology extraction, ambiguity detection, complexity analysis, constraint-driven optimization, optional expert review, and final target topology generation in the same input-compatible CSV structure.
At a high level, the solution reads the existing MQ environment, identifies producer-consumer flows, detects invalid and ambiguous patterns, measures current complexity, applies optimization decisions aligned to enterprise constraints, and produces a validated target topology along with comparison reports and explainable design decisions.
What makes the solution unique is that it does not only “clean the data” or “draw a graph.” It behaves like an intelligent architecture assistant: it understands the current topology, reasons about what is valid versus ambiguous, proposes a defensible target state, and preserves a human-in-the-loop path for edge cases.
Problem Statement
What problem are you solving?
Enterprise IBM MQ environments often grow organically over many years. As a result, they become highly interconnected, inconsistent, and difficult to manage. Applications may connect to multiple queue managers, routing paths become indirect and brittle, and queue ownership becomes unclear. This makes the environment hard to operate, modernize, secure, and automate.
This solution solves the problem of converting such complex legacy MQ topologies into a simplified, deterministic, and standard target architecture.
Who is affected and why does it matter?
This problem affects:
MQ platform and middleware teams
application teams that depend on messaging
operations and support teams
infrastructure automation teams
architecture and governance teams
It matters because topology complexity directly increases operational overhead, change risk, troubleshooting time, onboarding effort, and long-term maintenance cost.
What is the current pain point?
The current pain points include:
multiple queue managers per application
unclear producer-consumer ownership
complex or indirect routing paths
routing-only intermediate queue managers
alias-only or incomplete topology definitions
excessive fan-in / fan-out patterns
difficulty provisioning or changing MQ objects in a standardized way
inability to confidently automate due to inconsistent design
Why is the problem worth solving?
It is worth solving because a cleaner MQ topology provides:
lower operational risk
easier troubleshooting
better scalability
easier security and governance enforcement
automation-ready provisioning
faster onboarding and change management
a future-ready architecture instead of a brittle legacy network
Proposed Solution
High-level solution
The solution takes the AS-IS CSV topology as input and produces a TARGET CSV topology with the same schema, but with optimized content.
It works in six major stages:
Refined extraction
Parses the raw dataset into producer-consumer flow objects, including routing evidence, queue roles, ambiguity, and topology health.
Topology and complexity analysis
Builds queue-manager graph structures and measures flow-level and node-level complexity, including hop count, hotspots, routing-only QMs, broken flows, and orphan flows.
Optimization decision engine
Applies rule-based and topology-aware decisions to determine how each flow should be handled in target state:
preserve conceptually
canonicalize
split local-to-remote
simplify routing
exclude invalid flows
flag manual review where needed
Optional expert override layer
Allows controlled human-in-the-loop refinement for ambiguous or high-risk cases without breaking the automated pipeline.
Target topology generation
Produces a clean, canonical target flow model with one QM per app, deterministic routing, standard queue/channel naming, and target-state MQ objects.
Validation, comparison, and export
Validates target flows against constraints, compares AS-IS vs TARGET complexity, generates explanation reports, and exports the final target CSV in the original schema layout.
How it addresses the problem
It addresses the problem by:
reducing routing complexity
enforcing one QM per application
removing invalid and ambiguous topology from target design
generating deterministic QM-to-QM routing
preserving explainability for every transformation decision
making the output suitable for automation and enterprise review
